AIDS, eight fundamental non-communicable diseases
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart diseases, stroke, cancer, diabetes, and chronic lung diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that the use of tobacco, sedentarity, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of premature death from non-communicable diseases.
Yet, despite a wide knowledge of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to increase.
It was in this context that non-communicable disease alliances networks came together from December 9 to 11 at the Second Global Alliance for Non-Communicable Diseases Forum in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions to regulate MNTs, they should draw inspiration from the AIDS activist movement.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress made.
Although the battle is not over, AIDS activists know they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against MNTs can reverse this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, the editor of The Lancet journal, described the MNT community as being in wait for "an electric shock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from HIV/AIDS activists.
While the global attention is focused on preventing MNTs, those seeking to master preventable diseases should draw inspiration from the ABC of AIDS activist organizations.
The first letter that the MNT community must take into account is "A", as activism.
Anyone over 40 years old surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in "die-ins" at scientific conferences all around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets, even closing down the Food and Drug Administration headquarters for a day in October 1988.
At the global level, activists have been pressuring governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medications more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Next, the MNT community must adopt a bolder approach to budgets - the "B" of the HIV/AIDS movement's strategy.
Civic organization and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energies, but organizing and maintaining a large coalition requires money.
The HIV/AIDS movement has been clear about this from the beginning and has pushed for resources to effectively support its awareness and accountability activities.
"C" represents coalitions: the AIDS movement soon realized that progress comes only with multiple supports.
Activists established links between people living with HIV and those concerned with other issues, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Specialized coalitions and campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders to public authorities, combining their perspectives and expertise.
The AIDS movement also understood that a global response to the epidemic is essential to spreading its support.
Thus, "D", the determining factor of success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make informed decisions about protected sex relationships.
Similarly, links were established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a driving role in the HIV/AIDS crisis.
NCDs are no less isolated in their causality and also require a multi-sectoral approach to prevention.
The commitment - "E" - was what helped the HIV/AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the disability rights movement, which defended the slogan "Nothing About Us Without Us," HIV/AIDS advocates demanded representation from existing organizations to treat the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only UN agency with seats on its Board of Directors reserved for civil society representatives.
This standard is so deeply ingrained in the HIV/AIDS movement that it would be almost unimaginable for an AIDS conference to take place without community representation.
Disease prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives and "F" - framing the issue - is essential for the AIDS community to secure the support of political leaders.
Notably, access to AIDS treatments has been framed as an issue of economic justice.
Framing the story in this way has led to a significant reduction in medication prices, to the point where more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are receiving treatment.
A formulation equally important for HIV/AIDS, and very relevant to the NCD movement, is that of responsibility.
The HIV/AIDS community has worked hard to focus more on the life choices of individuals, rather than attributing responsibility to the state in the provision of healthcare and in the elimination of legal discrimination.
In the HIV/AIDS debate, gender - the "G" of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a "gay disease" and gender identity was rooted from the beginning in the DNA of the HIV/AIDS movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: one only needs to look at how alcohol and tobacco are commercialized to understand this.
The gender, therefore, must become a hub for MNT prevention efforts.
Finally, "H" - human rights - are the foundation of the HIV/AIDS response.
Campaigns have been launched against workplace discrimination, in schools, and in medical centers.
Strategic litigation has ensured equality under the law.
The HIV/AIDS movement has refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The MNT movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods to children.
We could continue listing lessons learned from the AIDS movement throughout the alphabet, but it seems appropriate to close with "H" given that human rights provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, and social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
The same is true for non-communicable diseases.
The initial reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to wonder: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS movement clearly said that this is not the right question.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The NCD and AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The views expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
